Billing Considerations for Unstructured Data and Search Index

When you use unstructured data and search index configurations, your data is stored and processed in Data Cloud. Use of Data Cloud features for unstructured data has billing implications. Use of Data Cloud services impacts the consumption of credits used for billing. There are four billing components for unstructured data in Data Cloud: data ingestion, data storage, data processing, and data queries. Each component has a distinct applicable usage type.

TYPE	DESCRIPTION	NOTES
Batch Data Pipeline	
Data Streams--Usage is calculated based on the amount of batch data processed by Data Cloud data streams across all connectors.
Data Transforms--Usage is calculated based on the higher of the number of rows read or number of rows written.
	Usage is calculated based on the number of records that are ingested either in batch or streaming mode by data streams. Unstructured data may be ingested through any Data Cloud connector. One of these usage types is used depending on the ingestion pattern used (batch or streaming).
Unstructured Data Processed	

Usage is calculated based on the amount of unstructured data that is processed. For example, if the search index processes 100 PDF documents that are 1 MB each, usage is calculated as 100 MB.

In Data Cloud, unstructured data may be chunked and vectorized using an embedding model. Usage is computed only once across both these activities. For example, if one 100 MB PDF document is chunked and vectorized, usage is computed as 100 MB, not as 200MB.

	
Accelerated Data Queries	Usage is calculated based on records processed. Certain types of queries such as Tableau queries and the data graph API are served with accelerated data queries.	

For vector search queries against unstructured data, the number of vectors in the search index are counted.

For hybrid search queries against unstructured data, the number of vectors and keyword records that are scanned are counted.


Storage Beyond Allocation	Usage is calculated based on the amount of storage used above the amount allocated.	

When a vector index is created using unstructured data, the chunk DMO and the vector DMO that are generated are counted towards storage.

When a hybrid search index is created using unstructured data, the chunk DMO and the vector DMO that are generated are counted towards storage.

Unstructured data and search index are not available for orgs using the Customer Data Platform (CDP). For more information on how Data Cloud usage is billed, refer to your contract or contact your account executive.
